From Contact to Gift: Party Organizations and the Vote Buying Pipeline in Mexico

How do parties convert organizational outreach into clientelistic distribution, and why are some parties more efficient at it than others? We investigate the contact-to-gift pipeline using party-specific data on six modes of campaign contact and party-specific vote buying measures from a post-electoral survey conducted after Mexico's 2015 federal deputy elections (N=1,200). We document three findings that challenge standard assumptions about how clientelistic distribution operates. First, party contact is the strongest individual-level predictor of gift receipt — within electoral precincts, being contacted by PRI predicts PRI vote buying (r=0.29) far more strongly than any demographic or programmatic characteristic, suggesting that organizational reach, not voter profiles, determines who receives gifts. Second, contact is not a necessary condition for gift receipt: 35 percent of PRI gift recipients and 61 percent of MORENA recipients report no prior contact from the distributing party, indicating that a substantial share of vote buying flows through diffuse community channels rather than direct party-to-voter pipelines. Third, among those contacted, the mode of contact matters in unexpected ways: phone contact is the strongest predictor of PRI gift receipt, while face-to-face canvassing — the mode most associated with broker operations — shows no independent effect, and digital contact modes (email, social media) negatively predict gift receipt. These patterns vary sharply across parties: PRI and PVEM convert roughly half of their contacts into gift recipients, while MORENA converts less than a quarter, reflecting deep asymmetries in organizational infrastructure inherited from Mexico's long period of single-party dominance. Rally attendance further illuminates the mobilization-clientelism nexus: 71 percent of rally attendees received vote buying offers compared to 48 percent of non-attendees, with neighbor-recruited attendees and those receiving transportation assistance showing the highest exposure. Together, these findings suggest that the organizational machinery connecting parties to voters — the phone trees, the rally logistics, the community intermediaries — matters more for understanding who gets bought than either the strategic targeting models or the voter-profile models that dominate the clientelism literature.






